               <head/>
               <msContents class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2006007951">
                  <summary>1 copy of Shāh-nāmah by Abū 'l-Qāsim Firdawsī</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="Uk_RSPA_23-item1">
                     <locus from="1v" to="441r"/>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_2149">Shāh-nāmah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_2149">شاهنامه</title>
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="ark:/81055/vdc_100000001088.0x0003b2 viaf_101359236">Abū 'l-Qāsim Firdawsī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" key="viaf_101359236">ابو القاسم فردوسی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa">سپاس وآفرین خدایرا جل جلاله که جهانرا وآن جهانرا آفرید</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">هزاران درود و هزاران سلام زما بر محمد علیه السلام</explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="ar">تمت الکتاب بعون الملک الوهاب فی غرة شهر ربیع الاول سنه ثمان والف بعد الهجرة النبویة المصطفوة علیه أفضل الصلوات وأکمل التحیة علی ید الفقیر المحتاج إلی رحمتهة الله الملک المنان فتحی ابن خواجه شاه محمود  </colophon>
                     <note>
                        <p>On f441v, Jones has written in black ink: "I finished the reading of this book a second time, 3 Nov. 1787 Calcutta". </p>
                        <p>The copyist's name is <persName key="person_f8196" role="scr">Fatḥī ibn Khwājah Shāh Maḥmūd</persName>.
                        </p>
                        <p>The quire of very thin white paper (ff.159-184) was added later by a second hand. It contains the story of Barzū and Sūsan. </p>
                     </note>
                     <decoNote>On both f1v and f2r there is a full page illuminated headpiece of blue and gold floral design. On f6v, the start of the poem proper, there is a much smaller headpiece above the beginning of the textblock. Gilded ruled margins.  </decoNote>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Very thin brown woven paper which has mostly been laminated for protection. One quire is composed of an even thinner white woven paper. </support>
                        <extent>ff.ii+441+iii<dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>310</height>
                              <width>180</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>230</height>
                              <width>120</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>Perso-Arab numerals in black ink (excepting the added-in quire). European numerals in pencil.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>Good condition. Guards and supports.</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="4" writtenLines="30">
                           <p>Poem is written in four columns of thirty lines. Preface is written in blank prose (one column per side). There are some folios (e.g.f439v-440r) which are written in geometric designs. There is a large stain on f49r.</p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc hands="1">
                     <summary>Very small and neat black ink nastaʿlīq. </summary>
                     <handNote script="Arabic" scope="major"/>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>
                        <p/>
                     </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p>There are marginal comments on almost every folio. These are predominantly in pencil by Jones and are in a mixture of English, Latin, Arabic and Persian. In some places he writes out the translation or transliteration of words or rewrites a difficult-to-read word (e.g.f6v, f166r - all notes of a linguistic nature). In other places he comments on the quality of the poetry (e.g. f378 or f12), narrates the story (e.g. f44v in which he narrates the story but gets it wrong and has to correcth himself). He also marks where he reaches in the text with the date (e.g. f377v).</p>
                     <p>There are some, very few, marginal notes in other hands, principally that of the scribe (e.g. f7r, f158v). </p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <p>Standard India Office half leather binding with wine coloured marbled endpapers. </p>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <accMat>
                     <p>There are many seals on f1r. Only one seal remains legible, that of ʿAbd al-Maʿbūd Khān. Others are partially legible. </p>
                  </accMat>
               </physDesc>
